rror between North and South.  ...    The price divergence reflects MISO's unique geography. The North-South constraint is contractual, not physical.  ...    MW southbound. During Fern, cheaper generation stayed trapped while prices spiked elsewhere. ​Minnesota's average real-time LMP across the storm reached $206/MWh. Illinois averaged $118/MWh. The 75% gap stems from congestion: Minnesota saw +$31/MWh average congestion while Illinois experienced -$42/MWh. Illinois could access cheaper sources of generation while Minnesota sat behind transmission bottlenecks. The divergence matters for BESS siting. A battery in Minnesota would have captured the $1,351/MWh spike. The same asset  ...    - Grid improvements have compressed the tail. Uri saw Minnesota TB4 spreads above $10,000/MWh. Fern delivered $2,873.  ...    - Storm capture is real, but location dependent. Minnesota offered $2,873/MW-day TB4 spreads, while Mississippi offered  ...    ### ​BESS is purpose-built for this kind of volatility.  ...    [California's batteries earned $1.81/kW in January 2026. The winter storm lifted peak"
